  "summary": "During a gathering, Mochizuki presents a theory regarding why the killer left the heads of Ito and Yokozawa undiscovered. He argues that the killer did not hide the heads out of fear of being caught, but rather to prevent investigators from conducting a search that might lead them to a specific \"sanctuary\" containing fatal clues. Mochizuki suggests the killer employed the concept of \"hiding the tree in the forest\" to conceal these locations.\n\nMuto and Mutsuji expand on this by hypothesizing that the killer utilized the Tomimura family's embalming room to hide remains inside coffins. They suggest the killer intended to prevent anyone from opening the coffins, thereby maintaining the illusion that they were empty. Following this logic, the narrator notes that Takao died a month prior. Mutsu concludes that if Kazuo Mochizuki did not actually die but instead woke from a coma inside a coffin, then Daisuke Inagaki is the perpetrator of the serial murders.\n\nMochizuki further explains that the deceased Tomita was likely the \"ghost\" Yuzuha witnessed, as his appearance could be mistaken for Akagi's in the dark. He also introduces an antique book titled \"Lekkunarawa,\" discovered in a church, which he believes inspired the double decapitation of Ito and Ushiwaka. Finally, addressing the \"Hell Gate\" room, Mochizuki suggests the house owner might possess a third key. He explains that a previous error occurred when Otoya mistakenly moved Hayato's corpse into the \"Hell Gate\" instead of Ito's, resulting in Hayato's left hand holding the key.",
